    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Monstrous men with two heads but only one body, literally, "one who has two heads" in Nahuatl. One of the omens predicting the arrival of the Spaniards.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109721/GRI, FloCo terminology (2019-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hombres monstruosos con dos cabezas pero un solo cuerpo, literalmente, "el que tiene dos cabezas" en náhuatl. Uno de los presagios que predice la llegada de los españoles.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109721/GRI, FloCo terminology (2019-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Tlacameh monstruos ica ome inintzontecon zanpampa pan ce tlacayoliztli. Ce tetzahuitl tlen quinextia quence ahcih caxtiltlacameh.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Eastern Huasteca Nahuatl</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
